{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602061/1937112701/0633.xml":{"full_text":"Surplus Tax\nPlea Goes\nUnheeded\nAdministration Is In\ndifferent to Busi\nness.\n\nRv DAVID LAWRENCE.\nAMERICAN business has pleaded\nwith the Roosevelt administra\ntion to do something about the\nundistributed surplus tax. The\nTreasury has indicated that it favors\nrevision. Congress has shown the\nsame attitude but there is nevertheless\na sort of rasualness and indifference\ntoward the fact that every American\nbusiness which lias a net income must\nknow between\nnow and Derern\nber 31 whether\nthere is going to\nbe a change in\nthe undistributed\nsurplus tax.\nNot only is it\nImportant to\nknow how to han\ndle the fourth\nquarter dividends,\n\"but also in most\ninstances it is vi\ntal to decide how\nmuch of what is\nearned in 1 9 3 7 |):l\nshall go into re\nserves and how much will have to be\npaid out lest a penalty be incurred.\nFor the present law penalizes a busi\nness for saving its money or for trying\nto expand and give employment.\nThe undistributed surplus tax was\nproperly termed last year, during the\ncampaign, a \"cockeyed piece of legis\nlation,\" but anybody who has studied\nthe effects of it would have difficulty\nin using such temperate language,\nfor it is the very reverse of prudence\nand the very opposite of common\nsense.\nSentiment Unanimous.\nSentiment for the repeal of the tax\nis almost unanimous, yet Congress\nhesitates. Chairman Vinson of the\nHouse Ways and Means Committee\nhas indicated to the press that he be\nlieves a law ran be drafted to exempt\n88 per cent of all the corporations. But\nthis is dealing with the subject by\nhalves. If the principle of the undis\ntributed surplus tax is wrong for some\nbusinesses, it is wrong for all busi\nnesses. As a matter of fact. 88 per\ncent of all the corporations might ac\ntually mean a small volume of the\ntotal sums earned that could Ire put\ninto business revival. It isn't the total\n1 number of the corporations, but what\nthey do and how much they earn that\ncounts in appraising the good or bad\neffects of tax legislation.\nThus 88 per cent of the corpora\ntions earn only about 10 per cent of\nthe taxable income. Corporations can\n'be formed very easily and there are lit\nerally thousands of corporations that\ndo a small volume of business. To put\nIt another way, 12 pel rent of the cor\nporations earn 90 per cent of the to\ntal taxable nrt income of American\nbusiness corporations.\nIt also would be found that the 12\nper rent employ most of the workers,\nbuy most of the raw materials and\ngenerally constitute such a big factor\nin the revival of business as a whole\nthat any change in the law which neg\nlects the 12 per cent is virtually no\nchange at all.\nRoosevelt Knows l aris.\nPresident Roosevelt is aware of the\nWidespread demand for revision of the\nundistributed surplus tax law, and he\ntold the press Friday that he wants\nsomething done at the earliest possible\nmoment. But he is also saying he\nwants a well-rounded tax program as\na whole and this means that until the\nwhole program is completed the ad\nministration doesn't want to do any\nthing about the undistributed surplus\ntax\nThis, however, does not meet the\npresent crisis What the business men\nwant to know is whether they must\ncount, on the undistributed surplus tax\nfor 1937. It is true they have until\nMarch 15 to make out their tax re\nturns, but it is this very month they\ndo much of their budg'et planning for\nthe calendar year 1938. and they must\nknow how much cash they must have\nleft after paying taxes.\nSenator George of Georgia, Demo\ncrat. says he wants the new tax re\nvision to be retroactive\u2014that is, he\nwants the calendar year 1937 to be\nfigured on the new rates. Others in\nCongress have expressed the same view\nend the Republicans in the House of\nRepresentatives are pressing this\npoint.\n\u2022vepeai v*ouia ne simple.\nIt would be a very simple matter\nfor both houses to put through over\nnight a repeal ol the undistributed\nsurplus by joint resolution. This\nmight also provide for a flat corpora\ntion tax or even a graduated income\ntax with narrow brackets, because the\nmoment the tax is placed on mere\nfrigness nr size of profits, incentive is\nkilled and the unemployment situation\nIs not cured\nThe President is saying to the news\npaper men that he does not want any\nhasty legislation and that his admin\nistration has been criticized for jam\nming measures through, but it seems\nIronical that a tax bill which was\nJammed through without full con\nsideration cannot now be repealed just\nas speedily when the whole country\nhas given mature consideration to the\nactual operation of the tax and con\nsiders It practically the most vicious\n'piece of lawmaking and deflation in\nthe whole economic history of the\nUnited States.\nNot Pushing Revision.\nThe administration is not pushing\ntax revision as earnestly or as effec\ntively as it might. The business men\nof America are entitled to know with\nin the next 20 days how to plan for\n1938 and the present business reces\nsion will not be relieved by the in\neptitude of Congress or the unwilling\nness of the Executive to make a turn\n\u2022about promptly. For the truth i.<\nCongress, far from being the inde\npendent institution it was reported\nto be when the special session was as\nsembled, is still controlled by rtibbei\nstamp leaders and rubber stamp fol\nlowers and one-man government stil\ncontrols the destinies of our economic\nsystem.\nIf the foregoing seems incredible tc\nsome who still believe in Congress a;\nft truly legislative body, let them note\nthis headline from a Washingtor\nmorning newspaper's front page with\nin the last day or so:\n\u201cHouse won't free tax aid bill unti\nRoosevelt asks for it: Ways and Mean\nCommittee to adhere to wishes o:\nPresident: action scheduled for nex\nsession.\u201d\nIn other words, the Ways and Mean;\nCommittee feels it can ignore the de\nmand for action now because it ha;\nnot suited Mr. Roosevelt to give Con\n_ gress the go-ahead signal. That\u2019s one\nmap government with a rubber stam]\nCongress.\n(Copyright. 1937.)\n4\nThe Capital Parade\nRoosevelt Eats Crow, Secretly Asking Southerners to\nHalt Congress Revolt.\nBy JOSEPH ALSOP and ROBERT KJNTNER.\nTHE most interesting phenomenon of the special session of Congress is\nthe cheerless bankruptcy of the administration leadership. The law\nmakers, maddened by the smell of depression in the air, are quite\nout of control.\nThe situation is so bad that, last week end, the President secretly ate\ncrow, calling in a Representative ot the same conservative Southern Demo\ncrats whom h' virtually cast out of the party last spring, inviting him and\nhis friends to kiss and make up w\u2019ith the administration, and asking for\nassistance from the powerful Southern group in handling the situation on\nthe Hill.\nThe chat was pleasant, although the President could not have much\nenjoyed it. After jollying the Southerner in the accustomed fashion, the\nPresident mentioued the serious state of affairs on the Hill, and admitted\nthat its cause was the depression.\nHe read a little sermon on the political dangers inherent in\ndepressions, putting especial emphasis on the fact that voters,\nenraged by bad times, rarely differentiate behceen conservatives and\nradicals, so long as they wear the same party label.\nHe urged that all Democrats ought to pull together, and he suggested\nthat the powerful Southerners put themselves behind the administration\nleadership in an effort to bring the\nCongress under some sort of con\ntrol\nActually, the plea was rather\nineffectual, although the South\nerner did agree that procedure\nought to be orderly. Indeed, during\nthe days since the chat, the situ\nation has grown worse to a point\nwhere the air is full of rumors of a\nsort of conservative coup d'etat.\nIt would probably be possible\nfor such Democrats as the Vice President, Senator James Byrnes of South\nCarolina. Senator Pat Harrison of Mississippi. Jesse H. Jones, and their like,\nto make alliance with independent New Dealers like Senator Joseph C.\nO'Mahonev of Wyoming, seize the reins in Congress from the White House,\ncut the gizzards out of the undistributed profits and capital gains taxes at\nonce, and make other concessions to business. And it is not altogether\nunimaginable that they will do so. They have already talked of it, rather\nnervously perhaps, among themselves.\n\nCrow is a rare item on the presidential menu, and the particular bird\nwhich the President swallowed in his recent private chat with the South\nerner was as large a crow, as fat and as unpleasant as it well could have\nbeen. His request to the Southerner was, to all intents and purposes, a frank\nconfession of error in having shouldered the Southerners aside in his quest\nfor a completely obedient congressional leadership.\nLast spring, when the past of Democratic leader of the Senate was\nvacated by Joe Robinson's death, the tight little Southern oligarchy which\nhad ruled the Congresses of the New Deal put forth Harrison as its candi\ndate for the succession.. The President and the men around him fought\nlike tigers for the election of Alben W Barkley of Kentucky, a Southerner\nby origin, but not by association, on whom they knew they could depend to\nOne senatorial vote for Barkley was procured at the last hour,\nin a three-cornered telephone conversation between a Senator\nalready pledged to Harrison, representatives of the White House, and\nrepresentatives of the malodorous Kelly-Hash machine in Chicago.\nThat single vole was deciding, and Senator Barkley was chosen to fill\nthp huge shoes of the big. hard-driving, straight-talking, much-respected\nRobinson by a majority of 1. The brand of leadership which he has shown\nsince the special session convened is in marked contrast to what the Senate\nknew under Robinson, and it may be blamed for the fact that the de\npression-inspired revolt of the Senators has already gone to such lengths\nthat nearly 40 of the 76 Democrats in the chamber have almost forgotten\nthat there's such a place as the White House.\n\nThe Kentucky Senator is an amiable, imposing-looking person, with\na pleasant manner, a talent for barber shop song, and a passion for tele\nphoning the White House.\nNot so long ago. during the anti-lynching bill gas attack which\nhr was pouerless to prevent. Senator Tom Connally of Texas called\nhim a \"Charlie McCarthy.\" Senator Connally hit a rather sore spot.\nA Charlie McCarthy was pretty much what the President wanted\ntor leader last spring, but now the President is finding that com\nmands carried by ventriloquism to a Congress in a disobedient mood\nare not altogether effective.\nAmong other troubles afflicting Senator Barkley is the additional\nfact that he longs to inherit the presidential succession in 1940. In conse\nquence, his leadership of the Senate is not only ventriloquistic; it is also so\nexceedingly friendly to other Senators who may have something to say in\nconvention delegations that it\nlacks a necessary force.\nThe Senator is genuinely lib\neral. he is able, he is extremely\neloquent. But these qualities do not\nmake up for his defects. Moreover,\nthe conservative Southerners who\nused to be Robinson's chief lieuten\nants are busily plotting against\nhim. The once-helpful Republican\nleader, the wise, cynical Charles L.\nMcNary of Oregon, is giving the\nSoutherners all the assistance he can. And the extremely influential and\nfoxy Vice President. John N. Garner, has practically dedicated his life to\nprocuring the revision of the tax laws and the defeat of the wages-and\nhours bill. Add to all this the effects of the depression, and the unhappy\nSenator's situation is all but hopeless.\n\nAs for the House situation, it is hardly better than that in the Senate,\nns the deadlock on the wages-and-hours bill has already demonstrated.\nThe definite coolness toward the wage-hour bill on the part of Speaker\nWilliam B Bankhead, the open opposition of the A. P. of L\u201e and. once\nmore, thp effects of the depression, have all combined to tangle up the\nPresident's program about as completely as passible.\nIn spite of the setbacks which the wage-hour bill has suffered re\ncently. Majority Leader Sam Rayburn and the New Dealers still hope to\nget the measure through. Their idea is to effect a compromise this week\nend between the 150 farm Representatives who oppose the wage-hour bill\nI and the 150 industrial district Representatives who have little enthusiasm\ni for the farm bill, and get the signatures to the petition bringing the wage\nhour bill out of the Rules Committee by these combined forces. To do so,\nhowever, they fear they may have to make concessions in the wage-hour bill\neven more sweeping than those already made. As one New Dealer put it:\n\"I guess we'll just have to pull out all the bill s real teeth,\nstick in some nice false uppers and lower in front, and pass it\nlike that.\"\n(Copyrlaht. lH.tr. by the North American Newspaper Alliance. Ine.)\nCITY NEWS IN BRIEF\nTODAY.\nMeeting, Biological Society, Oosmo6\nClub, 8 pm.\nDance, Beta Sigma Sorority, Alpha\nChapter, Kenwood Country Club, 10\np.m.\nDance, Young People of Epiphany\nChurch, Porestville, Md., and Christ\nChurch. Clinton, Md., Jr. O. U. A. M.\nHall. 2407 Minnesota avenue S.E., 9\np.m.\n\nMARRIAGE LICENSE\nAPPLICATIONS\nBon Watkins. 24. 211 11th st. s.w.. and\nSyblo McCubbin. 26. 2029 H st. n.w.;\nthe Rov. E H. Pruden.\nWalter F Souser 26. Johnstown Pa and\nElizabeth T Gleason. 26. 11 Nicholson\nst. n.w.: the R?v. W E. LaRue\nFrancis M Spindle. 21. Arlington. Va..\nand Dorothy M. Martin. 20. 612 Hamil\nton st. n.w.; the Rev S. C. Coale\nPhilip N. Triem. 24. 1626 Hobart st n.w..\nand Joan J. Haeringer. 20. isoi Irving\nst. n.w the Rev. M. W. Hvle\nHyle Prell. .-111. and Helen Miller. 25. both\nof New York City: the Rev J. c Ball\nHarold H. Clilt. 21. and Barbara E. Myers.\nIK both of Brentwood. Md the Rev\nA. F Poore.\nVaughn V Osburn. 23. Naval Air Station,\nand Mildred A Doolan. IK 6:!ti North\nCarolina ave. s.e.: the Rev. C. W. Nelson.\nFrank M. Solders. 2.o. and Olive C Lan\ncaster. 22. both of Caldwell. Idaho:\nJudge R. E Mattingly.\nShad Ravcrof! 2540 14th st nw\nand Emane Wright. 2:t, Arlington. Va\nthe Rev M P German.\nErnes' Young. 2M. Mil C. st. s.w.. and\nMary Lewis, 1242-A Half st. s.w.:\nthe Rev B. H. Whiting.\nJoseph S. Wade. 25. IKI5 18th st. nw.\nand Annabelle V. Meadow. 20. 1903 15tli\nst n.w the Rev. E. C. Smith.\nGeorge Gill M7. 1553 !tth st. nw. and\nHelen Williams. Ml. Wilson N. C.: the\nRov. J E. Graham.\nGeorge W. Jenkins. 30. and Hattie Aber\nnethy M4. both of 1504 13th st. n.w.:\nthe Rev. S. L. Michaux.\nAlexandria.\nRover. N Caldwell ir.. 24. and Kathleen\nM Murphy. 21. both of Washington\nNathaniel Ward 20. and Marlon Brown,\n\u2022-4. both of Alexandria.\nHoward Lee Wells. 28. and Bernice Brent\nnell. 20. both of Washington.\n\nBIRTHS REPORTED\nCnarles and Edna Harper, boy.\nElder and Mary Holohan, boy\nMichael and Camille McMahon, girl.\nGeorge and Alice Jones, girl.\nRuplno and Helen Jubane. boy.\nLovlniski and Virginia Mason, boy.\nRavmond and Helen Augustus, boy.\nJohn and Margaret O'Conner, boy.\nJohn and Mary Dunning, girl.\nJoseph and Ruth Dindlebeck. girl.\n1 Elmer and Mabel Durbin, girl.\nRobert and Ellen Beall boy.\nJames and Elizabeth Williams, boy.\nJohn and Mildred Green girl\nJames and Mamie Norris, girl.\nEmerson and Clarice Brown, girl.\nMelvin and Johnnie Brown boy\nRavmond and Helen Hawkins, girl\nAndrew and Georgians Barnes, girl.\nDEATHS REPORTED\nEdward B Rector. 83. 3525 TOth at.\nWilliam A. Hunter, 76, J 516 Pennsyl\nvania ave. s.e.\nRichard H. Meredith 76. 3011 8ih.it.\nGeorge H. Hosken. 73. 1616 33rd st\nMary Sullivan. To. St. Elizabeth\u2019s Hospital.\nPrank Souser. 6T. Emergency Hospital\nJoseph P. Miller. 61. :*H50 Wisconsin ave\nBruce L. Casteel. 61. Gallinger Hospital\nSamuel Ryan. 51*. Home for Aged and\nInfirm.\nAnnie Werzel. 57. 41*03 Georgia ave.\nRaymond S. Patton. 54 .31**20 McKinley st\nJoseph C. Howell, 40. Gallinger Hospital.\nFred H Robinson. 46. *2650 Wisconsin ave.\nPied C French. 44. Walter Reed Genera:\nHospital.\nAugust loner. 35. 3011 Alabama ave. a.e.\nJeanette Simmons. 11. Children's Hospital\nLottie Greene. 68. Freedmen s Hospital.\nKatherine Warren. 61, Freedmen's Hos\npital.\nAngeline Bracey. 60. Freedmen's Hospital.\nLuella Minor. 60, Gallinger Hospital.\nGeorge A. Sellers. 30. Emergency Hospital\nJames Stewart. 37 1017 Euclid st.\nMarie Gray. *27. Gallinger Hospital.\nHarold Williams. 8. Gallinger Hospital.\nInfant Brown. Gallinger Hospital.\n\nLoot Found With Pigs.\nConfession to the theft of $1,200\nfrom the state insurance offices ha.'\nbeen made by a government official\nof Knazhevatz. Yugoslavia. He led\nthe police to his pig sty in Burdina\nand disclosed the bulk of the loot hid\nden in a wall.\n'THE opinions of the writers on this page are their own, not\nnecessarily The Star\u2019s. Such opinions are presented in\nThe Star\u2019s effort to give all sides of questions of interest to its\nreaders, although such opinions may be contradictory among\nthemselves and directly opposed to The Star\u2019s.\n\"Acreage Allotments\u201d\nFarm Bill Gives Secretary oi Agriculture Wide\nAuthority Over Crop Quotas.\nBy MARK SULLIVAN.\nTHE farm bill now before the\nSenate provides for \"acreage\nallotments\u201d for all growers of\nwheat, corn, rice and tobacco.\n(Control of several other crops is ac\ncomplished by another law, the soil\nconservation act.*\nHow are these allotments arrived\nat? The language of the bill seems un\nn e c e ssarily In\nvolved. There are\nparts of it that\ndefy understand\ning. It must be\nthat they are only\nu n d e r s tood by\nsome one in the\nD e p a r tment of\nAgriculture who\nhelped to write\nthe bill, and knew\n.just what powers\nhe wanted, and\nwhat he meant to\ndo with the pow\ners when he gels _\nthem. However,\npatient study reveals that this is what\nthe bill will do:\nThe Secretary of Agriculture will\nallot \u201camong the several Slates and\namong the counties\" the acreage that\nmay be devoted to the production of\na particular crop, let us say wheat.\nThe basic figure for this acreage shall\nbe the average of the past 10 years,\nwith corrections for seasons of abnor\nmal weather and other factors. The\ncalculations are wholly in the hands\nof the Secretary of Agriculture and\nhis satisticians and advisers. The Sec\nretary's word is final. Pennsylvania\nmust raise for market no more wheat\nthan the Secretary of Agriculture de\ncrees. California must raise no more\nrice than the Secretary decrees. Iowa\nmust raise no more corn than the Sec\nretary decrees.\nCounties to Get Quota.\nWithin each State, each county is to\nbe given a quota. The county quotas,\nlike the State ones, are to be decreed\nby the Secretary of Agriculture at\nWashington. Within New York State.\nMonroe County must raise for market\nno more wheat than the Secretary of\nAgriculture decrees. Within Illinois.\nRock Island County must raise no\nmore corn than the Secretary of Agri\nculture decrees. Within California.\nSacramento County must raise no\nmore rice than the Secretary ol Agri\nculture decrees.\nHere, obviously, Ls a large power\ngiven to an official at Washington to\ndiscriminate among States and among\ncounties. The Senate Committee,\nwhich introduced the bill, apparently\nrealized this and tried to specify in\nas much detail as passible the factors\nwhich the Secretary of Agriculture\nmust take into account. They tried,\nso far as they could, to require him to\nbase the State and county quotas on\ndefinite figures. But the Secretary\nwas left much latitude of judgment.\nHe is allowed to exercise his judgment\nwith respect to \"trends in acreage.\u201d\nThat is an elastic phrase. If the\nacreage of wheat has been increasing\nin Illinois and if the Secretary thinks\nthis is a good trend, he can increase\nthe quota for Illinois. On the other\nhand, if he thinks this is a bad trend,\nhe can decrease the acreage.\nFurther, the Secretary is permitted\nto manipulate State and county quotas\non a basis which takes into account\n\u201cthe promotion of changes in soil\nconservation practices.\u201d That is an\nelastic phrase, too. It seems to mean\nthat if the Secretary thinks a whole\ncounty, or larger section, or even a\nwhole State, ought to be retired from\nraising wheat or cotton or what not,\nthe Secretary can bring this about,\nthough the bill limits him so that he\nwould be obliged to do this gradually.\nThe purpose in Mr. Wallace's mind\nmay be to restore parts of the \u201cdust\nbowl\u201d to nature by preventing the\nraising of any crops there. That, if\ndone with conscientious judgment,\nwould be wholesome.\nThe discretion which the bill gives\nthe Secretary would enable him to in\nfluence or determine the destinies of\nwhole States and sections. A political\nminded Secretary, or one holding cer\ntain theories of his own. or a Secre\ntary serving under a political-minded\nPresident, could reduce some States to\nward a condition of fallowness, elevate\nothers toward abundant production.\nNot only does the bill confer this\ngreat power of control over and dis\ncrimination among whole States and\nsections. It confers the san e power\nand the same discrimination over in\ndividual farms. Upon each farm is to\nbe imposed a quota. The work of al\nlotting quotas to individual farmers is\nto be done by \"local committees of\nfarmers,\u201d This is supposed to take\nthe curse of Washington bureaucracy\noff the assignment of quotas\u2014the\nquota for any one farmer is to be\nfixed by other farmers living in the\nneighborhood. Bui w here do these\nfarmers get their authority? They\nget it from Washington. They are\npaid by Washington. They have the\nstatus of official agents of the Depart\nment of Agriculture. Being official,\nthey have power of compulsion\u2014let\nj no one doubt that. The farmer must\ndo what they say, or else. farmer is\ncompelled to accept the quola they\nimpose upon him (subject to an intri\ncate. time-consuming and expensive\nright of appeal).\nIron Hand Concealed.\n\u201cLocal committee of farmers\" seems\na phrase of velvet camouflage to con\nceal the iron hand of Washington.\nNecessarily the local committee must\nget their instructions from Washing\nton. Washington can only carry out\nits large purpose by having each local\ncommittee do what Washington wants.\nOnly a Department of Agriculture ex\npert could understand the intricate re\nquirements upon which the individual\nfarmer's quota is based. The bill it\nseli says \u201cthe county agricultural agent\nshall be a member, ex officio, of the\ncounty committee.\u201d The county agent\n1 Is a direct representatne of the De\nI partment of Agriculture.\nI think the epitome of the crop con\ntrol here given is correct. I spent the\nwhole of Thanksgiving Day studying\nthe bill. If the bill bears any other\ninterpretation, I hope it will be\nbrought out\ntCopyright, 1937.)\nNature\u2019s Children.\nWoolly Bear Caterpillar.\nBy LILLIAN COX ATHEY.\nBrown and furry\nCaterpillar in a hurry.\nTake your walk\nTo the shady leaf or stalk.\nOr what not.\nWhich mav be the chosen *po\u2018\nNo toad spy you.\nHovering bird of prey past by you;\nSpin and die.\nTo live again a butterfly\n\u2014Christina Roaettl.\nWOOLLY BEARS live to be\nIsabella tiger moths, not\nbutterflies. Any sunshiny\nday you may see woolly\nbears sauntering along the path ahead\nof you. They are covered with a hairy\ncoat of several shades of brown or\nmaybe a deep rich brown that resem\nbles the winter coat of the brown\nbears.\nIf you happen to turn over a atone\nor bit of wood, you may And curled\nup and In a state of coma, a woolly\nbear. He is harmless and if you pick\nV\n'X\nhim up in your warm hands, holding\nhim cupped there, you will feel at\nfirst a faint stir of life, and in a short\ntime, the wee bear will be as chipper\nas you please.\nBeing the offspring of the hand\nsome Isabella moth who must live\nthrough the w\u2019inter in order to carry\non the traditions of the family this\ncaterpillar will interest you at once.\nNotice how he \u201cjust inches along-\u2019 as\nhe travels. He is possessed of 13\nsegments that work in unison. The\nlast two appear as one; don\u2019t let them\nfool you. There Is one pair of true\nlegs on each of the three front seg\nments which form the thorax, and\nthere are in addition four pairs of\nprolegs. These are on the third,\nfourth, fifth and sixth abdominal seg\nments. Last, but far from least, is\nthe sturdy proleg on the extreme end\nof the body. You can see why the\nwoolly bear can travel so fast and\nhold on so firmly with his tail\nclasper or proleg.\nWith his evenly clipped coat, ebony\ncolored head and two very tiny yellow\nwands. the caterpillar is really a\nstriking looking pedestrian when out\nfor a stroll. If you stoop jlown to\npick him up. the very breeze that your\nmovement makes causes him to pause\nin his hurry, and when you touch him\nhe curls up in a tight ball and re\nmains in this position for some time.\nHis bristly appearance fools his foes,\nthe birds. They have, every one of\nthem, during their career, mistaken a\ndainty tidbit for a bunch of sharp\nspines. The woolly looks too much\nlike a stiff brush to them and is let\nalone.\nThese caterpillars are fond of clover,\ndandelions and many grasses. These\nare absent during the winter in most\nof the caterpillars' haunts, and cold\nweather has a benumbing effect on\nthem; shelter is sought with the first\ncold days, though sunshine will\nawaken them during the coldest\nweather.\nIn late April, the woolly Is restless.\nHe seeks a secluded spot and spins a\nhandsome cell of silk with a feltlike\ntexture. The plump spinner tucks\nhimself in tight quarters and soon all\nyou see is a neat, compact cocoon.\nBy the last of May, the miracle of\nWe, the People\nSome Advice for Young Woman Who Wants to Assist\nCertain Legislation.\nBy JAY FRANKLIN.\nEAR MISS 138-Z:\nMy attention has been drawn to your advertisement In The\nWashington Star, in which you offer your valuable services to\nthose in need of special legislation:\nYOUNG SOUTHERN WOMAN, shrewd and clever, expert In political con\ntact matters, experienced in congressional and State legislative programs,\ndesires high-class affiliation with strong and appreciative organization\nseeking legislation this or next session of Congress. Box 1U8-Z. Star.\nI regret to say that I have no Job to offer you in my office, as there\nis a lot of legislation I would like to see passed, but I can and will offer\nyou my advice.\nI know you very well. Miss 138-Z.\n'46 2-,[ it You may be my dinner partner\nI the next time I dine out. You will\nV almost certainly attend the next\nV \\t big diplomatic reception. You\nhave a charmingly furnished and\n//eld} entirely discreet little apartment\nin an old made-over house in\nGeorgetown, with an old mammy\nin a turban who makes beaten bis\ncuit to go with the Smithficld\nham, dry Martinis and Scotch\nand-soda which you serve at your quiet little afternoon gatherings. You\ndress well and in good taste and talk amusingly about anything under\nthe sun In that soft, slurring, cute \"Southern accent\u201d of yours. You seem\nto have plenty of money\u2014though not too much\u2014and while every one\nknows you, nobody seems to know exactly where you came from or what\nyou are doing in Washington.\n\nHoney, the town is full of you. You get under foot. You seem to need\nprotection from a rough world crawling with multiple T. V. A.'s, income\ntaxes, wages-and-hours legislation, persecuted corporate surpluses and\nreciprocal tariff agreements. You sometimes appear at the theater, on the\narm of a bachelor Congressman who is on the Ways and Means Commit\ntee or one of those Senators from the back-steppes who feel like going\nnative in their second childhood. And, of course, you have tickets on the\n50-yard line at the Army-Navy game.\nThere's no doubt about it, you were born to have high-class\naffiliations with strong and appreciative organizations which need\nthe services of a good undercover girl. Feminine charm! That's\nwhat sells the 5-cent magazines, that's what puts the films across,\nthat's what peddles cigarettes and toothpaste, that the nay to slip\nthose little jokers into the big bills, that\u2019s what makes Congressmen\nperjorm miracles.\nIt's hard to think of a girl like you going begging. If the Liberty\nleague hadn't folded up like the best man at a bridegrooms bachelor\ndinner. I d send you right ov\u00abr to Jouett Shouse. Here's a little idea which\njust came to me out of the everywhere into the here. The American\nMedical Association is all set against Federal medical insurance, \"socialized\nmedicine\u201d or what-have-you, and the local medical group has recently\ndenounced the proposal to establish a medical co-operative in the Dis\ntrict of Columbia.\nWhy don't you see Dr. Morris Fishbein, Miss 138-X? He's the editor\nof the A. M. A. Journal, and no man is stronger than he in his opposi\ntion to \"regimentation\u201d of medical services. You could have a humani\ntarian field day. explaining to be\nwitched Congressmen how women\ndon't really need much care in\nchildbirth (\"Mali maw had six\nyounguns with only old Mammy\nLou and a little corn licker!\u201d?;\nwhat a blessing diphtheria, ap\npendicitis and cancer are to the\naverage household: how nothing _ t\nstimulates a man's ambition to VA i 1 1 I\ngain wealth and independence like 1 1\u2019\nhav ing his child die of scarlet fever 1\nbecause he can t afford a doctor; how nothing keeps a family anchored\nin a town like a load of medical debts it can't afford to pay.\n\nDr. Fishbein is obviously your man. Miss 138-Z. The American\nMedical Association may not be as wealthy as Commonwealth <fc South\nern or General Motors, but medical lobby work is mighty clean, fine work,\nand who could lobby more effectively against the proposal to help poor\npeople meet their medical emergencies than a young Southern woman,\nshrewd and clever, expert in political contact matters, experienced in\ncongressional and State legislative programs? Go forth In the fair name\nof Southern womanhood, honey, and do your stuff to keep other people\nmiserable.\n(Copyright. ln.\u2019tT.)\n\nANACOSTIA GROUP\nTO SEEK MEMBERS\nCitizens\u2019 Association Head Sug\ngests Disbanding Unless In\nterest Is Awakened.\nA widespread drive for active mem\nberships in the Anacostia Citizens\u2019\nAssociation was indorsed last night\nafter the meeting heard a plea by\nCapt. Frank M. Dent, veteran mem\nber of the association.\nShaking on the plan, the associa\ntion\u2019s president, H. E. Simensen. said\nthat unless more interest is shown in\nI the meetings, the association should\ndisband\n\u201cA group of 12 active citizens, as\nwe have here.\u201d Mr. Simensen said.\n\"certainly is too small to carry the\ni burden of responsibility of represent\nj ing a community numbering 7.500 peo\npie.\u201d\nMr. Simensen, who has served as\npresident of the association for two\nI years, deplored the inactiveness of\nthe community in the civic organiza\ntion. Pressed by veteran members\nwho have seen the body In existence\nsince 1895, he has continued as head\nfor three months after hating de\nclined the offer for renomination.\nThe scheduled meeting for Decem\nber falling on Christmas eve was\npostponed. The January meeting will\nview' the results of the membership\ndrive and determine if the associa\ntion is to continue.\nwitnessing a large, beautiful moth\ncreep from the small cocoon is awe\ninspiring.\nSlowly the moth of dull gray and\ntawny yellow makes his way from his\nshroud. On the middle of his body\nthere will be six black buttons. His\nhose are red, his shoes black. The\nbody is covered with soft fur. Gently\nthe crumpled wings are waved back\nand forth. The veins fill with air. the\nbody plumps, the handsome fellow\nrests awhile and soon is off in search\nof a mate. All this you may witness\nand feel that you have seen the resur\nrection of one of Nature's Children.\n(Copyright. 11*37.)\nFOUR RESTAURANT\nOPERATORS FINED\nPlead Guilty to Violation of\nHealth Regulation in\nPolice Court.\nFour local restaurant proprietors\npleaded guilty to violations of the\nhealth regulations before Police Court\nJudge Hobart Newman yesterday and i\nwere assessed fines of $20 and $25.\nThose arraigned and fined were:\nSamuel Hillow. operator of a res\ntaurant at Seventeenth and U streets\nN.W., $20: S. At L Baroco and Sol\nBaroco. through Sam Baroco. proprie\ntor of a restaurant at 617 Thirteenth\nstreet N.W., $20: Nick Triantis. whose\nplace of business is at 1917 Seventh\nstreet N.W.. $25, and James Cavades,\n1717 Seventh street N.W., $25.\nHillow was charged with having an\nunclean steam table, coffee urn,\nshelves, floor in kitchen, service room,\nmeat block, work tables, sidewalk and\nkitchen ceiling. He was also charged\nwith failing to provide a proper\ngarbage can.\nThe others were charged similarly\nbut with fewer offenses each.\nPULLMAN ASKS RAISE\nPiles 10 Per Cent Fare Increase\nRequest With I. C. C.\nCHICAGO. Nov. 27 (.Pi \u2014The Pull\nman Co. asked a 10 per cent increase\nin all Pullman fares in a petition filed\nyesterday with the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission.\nA company statement said Pullman\ntraffic volume showed a \u2018declining\ntrend of increase over the eorresuond\ning period in 1936'' and that the in\ncrease \u201cwas necessary in view of the\npronounced uptrend in the company's\noperating costs and taxes.\u201d\nHeadline Folk\nand What\nThey Do\nDr. Frank Boomed as\nStandard Bearer for\nRepublicans.\nBv LEMUEL F. PARTON\u2019.\nFOLLOWING an address befora\nthe State Federation of Wom\nen's Clubs In Albany arise sup\nplementary prophecies con\ncerning Dr. Glenn Franks further\ncareer, and prognostications are much\nless tentative and much more robust\ngenerally than earlier ones which\npromised distinc\ntion for him as\nkeynoter at the\nnext Republican\nNational Conven\nj tinn. For talk\nnow Is that the\n!:!i keynote speaker\nholding the plat\nform at the next\nforegathering of\nG O P. delegates\nwill be likely to\nfind Dr. Frank\namong the in\nterested listeners,\nJ.r. Glenn Frank. 8nd P^liaNy 1\"\nterested. inas\nmuch as he will be one of the leading,\nif not the leading, candidates for nom\nination as party standard bearer.\nIndeed, intimations of party prefer\nment have been heard ever since his\nLincoln's birthday address in Chicago\nin 1935. when he was still president\nof the University of Wisconsin. This\nspeech, in which he daringly attacked\ndemagogy in both great political par\nties, made a profound sensation in\nWashington, and, ever since, his utter\nances have commanded peculiarly\nclose attention among the time-tired\nmandarins of his party, whose silence\nin the face of a subtly developing\nboom may mean little, or, on the other\nhand, be very significant.\nHis trenchant animadversions at\nAlbany on current conditions, politi\ncal philosophies and empirical eco\nnomic devisings were quite definitely\nof the blazing keynote order and\nwill inevitably establish him more\nsignificantly In the popular mind, one\nway or another.\nThe Missouri cross-roads Is Dr.\nFrank's background centering in\nQueen City, where, m 1887. he was\nborn. Attending Kirksville State Nor\nmal School, he proceeded to North\nwestern University, taking a B A.\ndegree in 1912, following which he\nbecame assistant to the president of\nthe Evanston institution. He asso\nciated himself with the late Edward\nA. FUene of Boston in research and\norganization in 1919: was editor of\nCentury magazine in 1921 and presi\ndent of the University of Wisconsin\nin 1925. where his early success in\ncatching the overtones of this Pro\ngressive hinterland region was later\ncomplicated by various conflicts of\nviewpoint and educational and politi\ncal divagations, which led to his re\ntirement last year\n(Copyright, 1937.*\n\nSWANSON FAVORS PLANT\nOPENING AT ALEXANDRIA\nAdvises Citron Operation of Tor\npedo Station Would Not Inter\nfere With One at Newport.\nBt the Associated Press.\nSecretary Swanson yestordav ad\nvised Representative Citmn. Demo,\ncrat. of Connecticut that opera*ion\nof a torpedo station at Alexandria. Va\nwould not Interfere with operations\nof the one at Newport, R I.\nSecretary Swanson said the Navy\nbelieved it \u201cunwise\" to concentrate\nmanufacture of torpedos In any one\nplace. He wrote Mr. Citmn an ad\nditional station was desirable for ex\npansion. especially in case of war and\nadded if both stations operated at\nrapacity The Navy's needs for torpedos\ncould not be met for \u201cseveral years\nMr. Citron and Representative\nForand. Democrat, of Rhode Island\nprotested against opening the Alex\nanrirva torpedo basp as\"an auxiliary\nof the Washington Navy Yard.\nThe Navy Department, they said,\nwas seeking *5.000.000 to operate the\nstation, closed several years ago.\nMr. Forand said the Navy should\nenlarge the Newport station and\nmodernbre machinery there for torpedo\nproduction. He declared previous at\ntempts to manufacture torpedos in\nAlexandria resulted in \u201cNewport's\nhaving to make corrections in torpedos\nmade at Alexandria.\u201d\nt\nGrace Gray DeLont\nPsjrhic \"with the mra\ntlo UlMlilon tJM\"\nbeard over BOL. For\nsolution of perplexing\npersonal problems con\nsult this elear-seetne\nlife reader and adriser.\nPhone: MEt. 5 1 3 4\nPSYCHIC COt\u2019NCIL HOl\u2019SE.\nlion l'*th St. N.W.. Cor \u201cLM St.\nDEBUNKING DUNKING\nNO. 14 BY WILKINS COFFEE 6 TEA\n'THE DEBUTANTE DUNK\"\nThe finest finishing schools in\nAmerica feature Wilkins Coffee\nf.\nand the \u201cSugar-Tong Dunk\"